Experiment 3: Distance-Based RGB LED and Servo Control

Description
This experiment extends the previous project by adding an RGB LED to provide visual feedback on the measured distance.
The servo motor continues to change position according to the object's proximity, while the RGB LED changes colour
to indicate safe, warning, and critical distance zones.

Components Used:
-Arduino Uno
-HC-SR04 Ultrasonic Sensor
-SG90 Servo Motor
-RGB LED
-220 Ω Resistors
-Breadboard
-Jumper Wires

Code Logic:

-Green Zone (Safe Distance)
When the object is far from the sensor:

Distance > 30 cm
RGB LED = Green
Servo angle = 180°

-Yellow Zone (Warning Distance)
When the object moves closer:

Distance between 15 cm and 30 cm
RGB LED = Yellow
Servo angle = 90°

-Red Zone (Critical Distance)
When the object is very close:

Distance < 15 cm
RGB LED = Red
Servo angle = 0°

Features:
-Visual indication of object distance.
-Servo motor reacts to object proximity.
-Colour-coded distance monitoring system.
-Simple introduction to smart sensing applications.

Real-Life Applications:
-Parking assistance systems where coloured indicators guide drivers while reversing.
-Warehouse safety zones showing safe and dangerous distances around equipment.
-Industrial monitoring systems providing visual alerts when people approach hazardous machinery.
-Interactive exhibitions and installations where colours change based on visitor proximity.
-Smart home automation systems that indicate occupancy or proximity status.